comments.body:
@kcc arduinojson doesn't link to any code at all as far as I can say. Should be ready enough.

PS This is how fuzzer is built according to build logs:

clang++ -g -fsanitize=memory -fsanitize-memory-track-origins -fsanitize-coverage=edge,indirect-calls,8bit-counters -stdlib=libc++ -I../include fuzzer.cpp -o/out/json_fuzzer /usr/lib/libFuzzingEngine.a

This bug is pretty awful....

It's a result of bad casting in xmlValidateOneNamespace().

'ns' is an xmlNsPtr passed as an argument:

xmlValidateOneNamespace(xmlValidCtxtPtr ctxt, xmlDocPtr doc,
xmlNodePtr elem, const xmlChar *prefix, xmlNsPtr ns, const xmlChar *value) {

The structure looks like:
struct _xmlNs {
    struct _xmlNs  *next;       /* next Ns link for this node  */
    xmlNsType      type;        /* global or local */
    const xmlChar *href;        /* URL for the namespace */
    const xmlChar *prefix;      /* prefix for the namespace */
    void           *_private;   /* application data */
    struct _xmlDoc *context;            /* normally an xmlDoc */
};

This is cast to an xmlAttrPtr on the call to xmlAddId. The xmlAttr structure looks like:

struct _xmlAttr {
    void           *_private;   /* application data */
    xmlElementType   type;      /* XML_ATTRIBUTE_NODE, must be second ! */
    const xmlChar   *name;      /* the name of the property */
    struct _xmlNode *children;  /* the value of the property */
    struct _xmlNode *last;      /* NULL */
    struct _xmlNode *parent;    /* child->parent link */
    struct _xmlAttr *next;      /* next sibling link  */
    struct _xmlAttr *prev;      /* previous sibling link  */
    struct _xmlDoc  *doc;       /* the containing document */
    xmlNs           *ns;        /* pointer to the associated namespace */
    xmlAttributeType atype;     /* the attribute type if validating */
    void            *psvi;      /* for type/PSVI informations */
};

Note that these structures have some overlapping elements, but are far from equivalent, with xmlAttr being a fair bit larger.

On a call to xmlAddID, the 'ns' structure is cast to a larger attr structure:
    /* Validity Constraint: ID uniqueness */
    if (attrDecl->atype == XML_ATTRIBUTE_ID) {
        if (xmlAddID(ctxt, doc, value, (xmlAttrPtr) ns) == NULL)
            ret = 0;
    }

Towards the end of xmlAddID, a structure member past the end of the 'ns' structure is set:

    if (attr != NULL)
        attr->atype = XML_ATTRIBUTE_ID;
    return(ret);
}

The ASAN crash is from the write to the 'atype' member past the end of the 'ns' structure.

Also, a pointer to the 'ns' structure, supposedly an attr structure, is saved in the returned ID structure:
        ret->attr = attr;

Right below the call to xmlAddID(), I see the NS structure cast to a 'xmlChar *' on a call to xmlAddRef().

    if ((attrDecl->atype == XML_ATTRIBUTE_IDREF) ||
        (attrDecl->atype == XML_ATTRIBUTE_IDREFS)) {
        if (xmlAddRef(ctxt, doc, value, (xmlAttrPtr) ns) == NULL)
            ret = 0;
    }

Within xmlAddRef(), the structure pointer is passed to xmlStrdup. This could possibly be an infoleak.

Re: Android fix

Was this fix materially different than the fix posted to upstream Bug 780228?
<https://bugzilla.gnome.org/show_bug.cgi?id=780228>

diff --git a/valid.c b/valid.c
index 19f84b82..aee6f40f 100644
--- a/valid.c
+++ b/valid.c
@@ -4623,13 +4623,13 @@ xmlNodePtr elem, const xmlChar *prefix, xmlNsPtr ns, const xmlChar *value) {

     /* Validity Constraint: ID uniqueness */
     if (attrDecl->atype == XML_ATTRIBUTE_ID) {
-        if (xmlAddID(ctxt, doc, value, (xmlAttrPtr) ns) == NULL)
+        if (xmlAddID(ctxt, doc, value, (xmlAttrPtr) attrDecl) == NULL)
      ret = 0;
     }

     if ((attrDecl->atype == XML_ATTRIBUTE_IDREF) ||
  (attrDecl->atype == XML_ATTRIBUTE_IDREFS)) {
-        if (xmlAddRef(ctxt, doc, value, (xmlAttrPtr) ns) == NULL)
+        if (xmlAddRef(ctxt, doc, value, (xmlAttrPtr) attrDecl) == NULL)
      ret = 0;
     }
